---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Tooltip from '../components/Tooltip.astro';
import '../styles/global.css';


---

<Base title="How to bet (and win)">
  <main class="px-4 sm:px-6" style="overflow-x: hidden;">
    {/* ─── Header ─── */}
    <header class="max-w-prose mx-auto pt-20 pb-16 sm:pt-28 sm:pb-20">
      <h1 class="text-ink">How to bet (and win)</h1>
      <p class="mt-3 text-ink/60 italic" style="font-size: 1.05rem;">
        An interactive explainer on the Kelly Criterion and gambler's ruin.
      </p>
    </header>

    {/* ─── Section 1: The opening question ─── */}
    <section id="opening" class="max-w-prose mx-auto pb-20">
      <div class="flex items-start gap-4 mb-8">
        <img src="/chip-1.png" alt="" width="48" height="48" class="section-chip-img hidden sm:block" />
        <h2 class="mt-0" style="margin-top: 0;">
          <img src="/chip-1.png" alt="" width="32" height="32" class="section-chip-img inline sm:hidden mr-2 align-middle" />
          The opening question
        </h2>
      </div>

      <p class="text-body leading-relaxed">
        A coin pays even money<Tooltip text="If you bet £1 and win, you get £1 profit (plus your £1 back). If you lose, you're out £1." id="tooltip-even-money" /> and lands heads 55% of the time. You have £1,000 in your account. How much do you bet?
      </p>

      {/* Slider + Button */}
      <div class="mt-10 mb-6" id="bet-controls">
        <label for="bet-slider" class="block mb-3 font-medium">Your bet</label>
        <input
          type="range"
          id="bet-slider"
          min="0"
          max="1000"
          step="10"
          value="0"
          aria-valuemin="0"
          aria-valuemax="1000"
          aria-valuenow="0"
          aria-valuetext="£0"
        />
        <div class="mt-3 text-center">
          <span class="font-mono text-lg" id="bet-readout">£0</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="text-center mt-8" id="bet-button-container">
        <button
          type="button"
          id="lock-bet"
          class="btn-primary"
        >
          Lock in my bet
        </button>
      </div>

      {/* Response panel */}
      <div class="response-panel mt-10" id="response-panel" aria-live="polite">
        <div class="border-l-2 border-card-red pl-5 py-2">
          <p id="response-text" class="mb-4"></p>
          <a
            href="#edge"
            class="text-sm text-gold no-underline hover:underline"
            style="text-decoration: none;"
            id="scroll-link"
          >scroll to see why ↓</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* ─── Section 2: Building intuition - edge ─── */}
    <section id="edge" class="max-w-prose mx-auto py-20 border-t border-ink/10">
      <div class="flex items-start gap-4 mb-8">
        <img src="/chip-2.png" alt="" width="48" height="48" class="section-chip-img hidden sm:block" />
        <h2 class="mt-0" style="margin-top: 0;">
          <img src="/chip-2.png" alt="" width="32" height="32" class="section-chip-img inline sm:hidden mr-2 align-middle" />
          Building intuition: edge
        </h2>
      </div>

      {/* ─── Part 1: Prose ─── */}
      <p>Every bet has two numbers: the probability you win, and how much you win if you do. Neither alone tells you whether the bet is worth taking. A 20% chance to win at 10:1 payout is a great bet; a 20% chance at 2:1 is a terrible one. We need a single number that combines both.</p>

      <p>That number is <strong>edge</strong>: how much money you expect to make, on average, for every £1 you stake.</p>

      <p>For a bet with win probability <em>p</em>, loss probability <em>q</em>&nbsp;=&nbsp;1&nbsp;−&nbsp;<em>p</em>, and net payout <em>b</em>&nbsp;:&nbsp;1 (meaning: stake £1, win £<em>b</em> profit if successful, lose your £1 if not), edge is:</p>

      <div class="formula">
        <strong>edge</strong> = <em>bp</em> − <em>q</em>
      </div>

      <p>Positive edge means you expect to make money. Zero edge means you break even on average. Negative edge means you expect to lose (which is why casinos exist).</p>

      <p>The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelly_criterion" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Kelly Criterion</a> takes edge and tells you what fraction of your bankroll to bet:</p>

      <div class="formula">
        <em>f</em> <sup>*</sup> = edge / <em>b</em>
      </div>

      <p>The formula captures the full picture: bet more when edge is large, and bet less when the payout <em>b</em> is large. A bigger <em>b</em> means rarer wins, so you can go through long losing runs before the payoff arrives. Kelly shrinks your bet to keep you solvent through those runs.</p>

      <p class="italic" style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: rgba(26,26,26,0.5); padding-left: 1rem; border-left: 2px solid rgba(26,26,26,0.08);">The formula is named after John Kelly Jr., a Bell Labs researcher who derived it in 1956 in a paper on information theory. He wasn't trying to solve a gambling problem - he was trying to understand how much information a noisy communication channel could carry, and betting happened to be the cleanest way to frame the maths. Kelly himself never used the formula to make money. He died at 41, in 1965, without publishing anything else on the topic.</p>

      <p>Try it below. Drag the probability and payout sliders, and watch edge, fair odds, and the Kelly fraction update. Then click one of the reference chips below the calculator: each applies the parameters of a real-world bet so you can see how edge behaves across orders of magnitude.</p>

      {/* ─── Part 2: Edge calculator ─── */}
      <div class="mt-12 mb-8" id="edge-calculator">
        <div class="mb-8">
          <label for="p-slider" class="block mb-2 font-medium">Win probability (<em>p</em>)</label>
          <input
            type="range"
            id="p-slider"
            min="1"
            max="999"
            step="1"
            value="550"
            aria-valuemin="0.1"
            aria-valuemax="99.9"
            aria-valuenow="55.0"
            aria-valuetext="55.0%"
          />
          <div class="mt-2 text-center">
            <output for="p-slider" class="font-mono text-lg" id="p-readout">55.0%</output>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="mb-8">
          <label for="b-slider" class="block mb-2 font-medium">Payout (<em>b</em>&thinsp;:&thinsp;1)</label>
          <input
            type="range"
            id="b-slider"
            min="0"
            max="1000"
            step="1"
            value="137"
            aria-valuenow="1.0"
            aria-valuetext="1.0 : 1"
          />
          <div class="mt-2 text-center">
            <output for="b-slider" class="font-mono text-lg" id="b-readout">1.0 : 1</output>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="readout-grid">
          <div class="readout-card">
            <div class="readout-label">Edge (per £1 staked)</div>
            <output for="p-slider b-slider" class="readout-value block" id="edge-output">+£0.10</output>
          </div>
          <div class="readout-card">
            <div class="readout-label">Fair payout (<em>b</em> for zero edge)</div>
            <output for="p-slider" class="readout-value block" id="fair-output">0.82 : 1</output>
            <div class="readout-caption">the payout you'd need for a break-even bet at this probability</div>
          </div>
          <div class="readout-card">
            <div class="readout-label">What % of your money to bet</div>
            <output for="p-slider b-slider" class="readout-value block" id="kelly-output">10.00%</output>
            <div class="readout-caption" id="kelly-caption">the Kelly fraction, <em>f</em><sup class="text-[0.65em]">*</sup></div>
          </div>
          <div class="readout-card readout-card-hero">
            <div class="readout-label">Suggested bet on £1,000 bankroll</div>
            <output for="p-slider b-slider" class="readout-value block text-card-red font-bold" id="bet-s2-output">£100</output>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      {/* ─── Part 3: Reference chips ─── */}
      <div class="preset-chips" id="preset-chips" role="group" aria-label="Reference bet presets">
        <button type="button" class="preset-chip" data-preset="lottery"
          aria-label="Lottery: UK National Lotto. p = 1 in 45 million, £2 ticket, £3.8m jackpot. One of the worst bets you'll encounter.">
          Lottery
          <span class="chip-tooltip">UK National Lotto. p&nbsp;=&nbsp;1 in 45&nbsp;million, £2 ticket, £3.8m jackpot. One of the worst bets you'll encounter.</span>
        </button>
        <button type="button" class="preset-chip" data-preset="us-roulette"
          aria-label="US Roulette: American roulette, red/black. Two green zeros give the house a 5.26% edge, nearly double European roulette.">
          US Roulette
          <span class="chip-tooltip">American roulette, red/black. Two green zeros (0 and 00) give the house a 5.26% edge, nearly double European roulette.</span>
        </button>
        <button type="button" class="preset-chip" data-preset="eu-roulette"
          aria-label="EU Roulette: European roulette, red/black. One green zero gives the house a 2.70% edge, half the house edge of the American version.">
          EU Roulette
          <span class="chip-tooltip">European roulette, red/black. One green zero gives the house a 2.70% edge, half the house edge of the American version.</span>
        </button>
        <button type="button" class="preset-chip" data-preset="fair-coin"
          aria-label="Fair Coin: A fair coin paying even money. Zero edge. Kelly says don't play; the house can't beat you, but gambler's ruin eventually will.">
          Fair Coin
          <span class="chip-tooltip">A fair coin paying even money. Zero edge. Kelly says don't play; the house can't beat you, but gambler's ruin eventually will.</span>
        </button>
        <button type="button" class="preset-chip" data-preset="biased-coin"
          aria-label="Biased Coin: The coin from the opening question. A small positive edge. Kelly: bet 10% of your bankroll.">
          Biased Coin
          <span class="chip-tooltip">The coin from the opening question. A small positive edge. Kelly: bet 10% of your bankroll.</span>
        </button>
        <button type="button" class="preset-chip" data-preset="card-counter"
          aria-label="Card Counter: A skilled blackjack card counter's edge when the count is favourable. Thin edge, tiny bets, long grind.">
          Card Counter
          <span class="chip-tooltip">A skilled blackjack card counter's edge when the count is favourable. Thin edge, tiny bets, long grind.</span>
        </button>
        <button type="button" class="preset-chip" data-preset="vc"
          aria-label="Pre-seed VC: A pre-seed venture capital investment. Roughly 10% of investments return 20× or more; the rest go to zero. Large positive edge, but enormous variance.">
          Pre-seed VC
          <span class="chip-tooltip">A pre-seed venture capital investment. Roughly 10% of investments return 20× or more; the rest go to zero. Large positive edge, but enormous variance, which is why VCs diversify across 20–30 portfolio companies.</span>
        </button>
      </div>

      {/* ─── Part 4: Transition prose ─── */}
      <p class="mt-12">Notice how the pre-seed VC's fraction is only 5.5%, despite the enormous edge. Notice how even a 55/45 coin has you only betting 10%. The formula is conservative for a reason. The next section shows you why.</p>

      <div class="text-center mt-6">
        <a
          href="#simulator"
          class="text-sm text-gold"
          style="text-decoration: none;"
          id="scroll-to-s3"
        >scroll to see why ↓</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* ─── Section 3: The main event ─── */}
    <section id="simulator" class="max-w-prose mx-auto py-20 border-t border-ink/10">
      <div class="flex items-start gap-4 mb-8">
        <img src="/chip-3.png" alt="" width="48" height="48" loading="lazy" class="section-chip-img hidden sm:block" />
        <h2 class="mt-0" style="margin-top: 0;">
          <img src="/chip-3.png" alt="" width="32" height="32" loading="lazy" class="section-chip-img inline sm:hidden mr-2 align-middle" />
          The main event
        </h2>
      </div>

      <p>Kelly gives you a number. The simulator lets you disobey it. Pick your bet, pick how much of Kelly to actually wager, and run it a thousand times to see what you'd have ended up with.</p>

      {/* Controls */}
      <div class="mt-10">
        <div class="sim-control-group">
          <label>Starting bankroll</label>
          <div class="paths-btn-group">
            <button type="button" class="paths-btn is-active" data-bankroll="1000">£1k</button>
            <button type="button" class="paths-btn" data-bankroll="10000">£10k</button>
            <button type="button" class="paths-btn" data-bankroll="100000">£100k</button>
            <button type="button" class="paths-btn" data-bankroll="10000000">£10M</button>
            <button type="button" class="paths-btn" data-bankroll="100000000">£100M</button>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="sim-control-group">
          <label for="sim-p">Win probability (<em>p</em>)</label>
          <input type="range" id="sim-p" min="1" max="999" step="1" value="550" />
          <div class="mt-1 text-center">
            <output for="sim-p" class="font-mono text-sm" id="sim-p-readout">55.0%</output>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="sim-control-group">
          <label for="sim-b">Payout (<em>b</em>&thinsp;:&thinsp;1)</label>
          <input type="range" id="sim-b" min="0" max="3000" step="1" value="1000" />
          <div class="mt-1 text-center">
            <output for="sim-b" class="font-mono text-sm" id="sim-b-readout">1.0 : 1</output>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="sim-control-group">
          <label for="sim-rounds">Number of bets <Tooltip text="How many bets you make in a single lifetime. A roulette session might be 500 spins; a card counter grinds out 2,000 hands; a pre-seed VC makes maybe 30-50 investments over a fund's lifetime; a PE fund might do 15 deals." id="tt-num-bets" /></label>
          <input type="range" id="sim-rounds" min="10" max="2000" step="10" value="500" />
          <div class="mt-1 text-center">
            <output for="sim-rounds" class="font-mono text-sm" id="sim-rounds-readout">500</output>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      {/* Scenarios */}
      <div class="mt-8">
        <label class="block mb-2 font-medium" style="font-size: 0.9rem;">Scenarios</label>
        <div class="scenario-grid" role="group" aria-label="Scenario presets">
          <button type="button" class="scenario-btn" data-scenario="fair-coin">
            <Tooltip text="A fair coin paying even money. Zero edge. Kelly says don't play - you won't go broke any faster than you would at a casino, but you won't get anywhere either." id="tt-fair-coin" />
            <span class="scenario-icon">⚪</span>
            <span class="scenario-name">Fair Coin</span>
            <span class="scenario-sub">p=0.50, b=1.0</span>
          </button>
          <button type="button" class="scenario-btn" data-scenario="eu-roulette">
            <Tooltip text="European roulette, betting red or black. The single green zero gives the house a 2.7% edge. Kelly returns a negative fraction - mathematically, the correct bet is not to play." id="tt-eu-roulette" />
            <span class="scenario-icon">🎡</span>
            <span class="scenario-name">EU Roulette</span>
            <span class="scenario-sub">p=0.4865, b=1.0</span>
          </button>
          <button type="button" class="scenario-btn" data-scenario="us-roulette">
            <Tooltip text="American roulette, betting red or black. Two green zeros (0 and 00) give the house a 5.3% edge - nearly double European roulette, for the same game." id="tt-us-roulette" />
            <span class="scenario-icon">🎰</span>
            <span class="scenario-name">US Roulette</span>
            <span class="scenario-sub">p=0.4737, b=1.0</span>
          </button>
          <button type="button" class="scenario-btn" data-scenario="biased-coin">
            <Tooltip text="The coin from the opening question. 55% win rate, paying even money. A small positive edge. Kelly: bet 10% of your bankroll each round." id="tt-biased-coin" />
            <span class="scenario-icon">🪙</span>
            <span class="scenario-name">Biased Coin</span>
            <span class="scenario-sub">p=0.55, b=1.0</span>
          </button>
          <button type="button" class="scenario-btn" data-scenario="card-counter">
            <Tooltip text="A skilled blackjack card counter's edge when the count is favourable. Thin positive edge, tiny bets, long grind. This is what actual professional gambling looks like." id="tt-card-counter" />
            <span class="scenario-icon">🃏</span>
            <span class="scenario-name">Card Counter</span>
            <span class="scenario-sub">p=0.51, b=1.0</span>
          </button>
          <button type="button" class="scenario-btn" data-scenario="sports-gambler">
            <Tooltip text="A winning sports bettor. Breaking even requires a 52.4% win rate because of the bookmaker's cut; sharps sustain 53-55%. Modelled here as a 54% win rate at -110 odds." id="tt-sports" />
            <span class="scenario-icon">🏈</span>
            <span class="scenario-name">Sharp Sports</span>
            <span class="scenario-sub">p=0.54, b=0.909</span>
          </button>
          <button type="button" class="scenario-btn" data-scenario="pre-seed-vc">
            <Tooltip text="Writing £250k cheques into early-stage startups. Roughly 10% of investments return 20× or more; the rest go to zero. Large positive edge, enormous variance - why VCs diversify across 30+ portfolio companies." id="tt-pre-seed" />
            <span class="scenario-icon">🚀</span>
            <span class="scenario-name">Pre-seed VC</span>
            <span class="scenario-sub">p=0.1, b=20</span>
          </button>
          <button type="button" class="scenario-btn" data-scenario="growth-vc">
            <Tooltip text="Later-stage venture investing. Companies are de-risked, valuations are higher. Lower hit rate than pre-seed (~30%), smaller multiples (~3×). Different shape of power law, same basic maths." id="tt-growth-vc" />
            <span class="scenario-icon">📈</span>
            <span class="scenario-name">Growth VC</span>
            <span class="scenario-sub">p=0.3, b=3</span>
          </button>
          <button type="button" class="scenario-btn" data-scenario="private-equity">
            <Tooltip text="Buyout investing in mature companies. Historical data shows ~85% of deals return at least their invested capital, with successful deals typically achieving 2-3x MOIC (we use 1.5x profit as a middle estimate). The high win rate means Kelly recommends heavy concentration - which is exactly why PE funds really do concentrate into 10-20 deals per fund. In real life, fund structure and hold periods prevent the extreme growth rates the simulator shows. That's a pedagogical feature: Kelly's answer and operational reality diverge here." id="tt-pe" />
            <span class="scenario-icon">🏢</span>
            <span class="scenario-name">Private Equity</span>
            <span class="scenario-sub">p=0.85, b=1.5</span>
          </button>
        </div>
      </div>

      {/* Figure 1: Kelly curve (analytical) */}
      <figure class="mt-10 mb-2">
        <div id="chart-kelly-curve" class="sim-chart-container" role="img" aria-label="Theoretical growth rate by Kelly multiplier"></div>
        <figcaption>Figure 1 - Theoretical growth rate by Kelly multiplier. Your current choice is marked. Above 2x, growth goes negative: even a positive-edge bet loses money on average.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      {/* Kelly strategies block */}
      <div class="kelly-strategy-block my-10 py-8" id="kelly-strategy-block">
        <div class="text-center mt-2 mb-6 font-serif" style="font-size: 1.55rem; line-height: 1.3; color: #1a1a1a;" id="kelly-says"></div>
        <div class="kelly-btn-row" role="group" aria-label="Kelly strategy multipliers">
          <div class="kelly-btn-wrap">
            <button type="button" class="kelly-btn" data-kelly-mult="0.25">Bet a quarter<span class="kelly-btn-sub">Quarter Kelly</span></button>
          </div>
          <div class="kelly-btn-wrap">
            <button type="button" class="kelly-btn" data-kelly-mult="0.5">Bet half<span class="kelly-btn-sub">Half Kelly</span></button>
          </div>
          <div class="kelly-btn-wrap">
            <button type="button" class="kelly-btn kelly-btn-rec is-active" data-kelly-mult="1">Bet what Kelly says<span class="kelly-btn-sub">Full Kelly</span></button>
          </div>
          <div class="kelly-btn-wrap">
            <button type="button" class="kelly-btn" data-kelly-mult="2.1" style="position: relative;"><Tooltip text="2× Kelly is the mathematical cliff - bet any more than that and your long-run growth rate turns negative, even with a positive edge. 2.1× puts you just over the edge so you can see what that collapse actually looks like." id="tt-over-kelly" />Bet double<span class="kelly-btn-sub">Over-Kelly</span></button>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="bet-summary-grid" id="bet-summary">
          <div class="bet-summary-col">
            <div class="bet-summary-header">Your odds of winning <Tooltip text="Your probability of winning on a single bet. 75% means you win 3 out of 4 times on average. This is the 'p' parameter from the Kelly formula - combined with the payout, it determines whether a bet is worth taking and how much to stake." id="tt-odds" /></div>
            <div class="bet-summary-value" id="summary-odds">55.0%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="bet-summary-col">
            <div class="bet-summary-header">If you win, you make <Tooltip text="Your profit on a winning bet, not counting your original stake. If you bet £100 at even-money odds and win, you make £100 profit (and get your £100 stake back too, so £200 total). If you bet £100 at 20:1 odds and win, you make £2,000 profit." id="tt-win-payout" /></div>
            <div class="bet-summary-value" id="summary-payout">£100</div>
          </div>
          <div class="bet-summary-col">
            <div class="bet-summary-header">Your bet</div>
            <div class="bet-summary-value text-card-red font-bold" id="summary-bet">£100</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      {/* Run button + Reset */}
      <div class="mt-8 mb-1 text-center">
        <button type="button" id="sim-run" class="btn-primary" style="font-size: 0.95rem; padding: 0.6rem 2.5rem;">Run simulation</button>
      </div>
      <div class="text-center mb-8">
        <a href="#" id="sim-reset" class="text-sm text-ink/40 hover:text-ink/60" style="text-decoration: none; font-style: italic;">Reset</a>
      </div>

      {/* Figure 2: Log-wealth trajectories */}
      <figure class="mb-8">
        <div id="chart-wealth" class="sim-chart-container" role="img" aria-label="Bankroll trajectory chart showing median and percentile bands">
          <div class="sim-chart-placeholder"><span class="text-card-red" style="font-size: 1.4rem; display: block; margin-bottom: 0.4rem;">♠</span><span style="font-variant: small-caps; font-style: italic;">Run the simulation to see the result</span></div>
        </div>
        <figcaption id="chart-wealth-caption">Figure 2 - Median bankroll trajectory, with 10th to 90th percentile band.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      {/* Stats */}
      <div class="readout-grid" id="sim-stats" aria-live="polite">
        <div class="readout-card">
          <div class="readout-label">% of paths that beat starting bankroll</div>
          <output class="readout-value block" id="stat-beat">-</output>
        </div>
        <div class="readout-card">
          <div class="readout-label">Bankruptcy rate</div>
          <output class="readout-value block" id="stat-bankrupt">-</output>
        </div>
        <div class="readout-card">
          <div class="readout-label">Mean final wealth</div>
          <output class="readout-value block" id="stat-mean">-</output>
          <div class="readout-caption">mean can be misleading when the distribution is skewed; look at median too</div>
        </div>
        <div class="readout-card readout-card-hero">
          <div class="readout-label">Median final wealth <Tooltip text="The median is the middle outcome - half of simulated paths ended above this number, half below. We lead with median because it's what you'd actually experience: run this bet a thousand times and half your lives end up here or worse. The mean is pulled upward by a few lucky paths that got rich early and compounded, so it can look great even when most outcomes are dismal. When median and mean diverge sharply, the distribution is skewed." id="tt-median" /></div>
          <output class="readout-value block text-card-red font-bold" id="stat-median">-</output>
        </div>
      </div>

      {/* Transition prose */}
      <div class="mt-12">
        <p>Try the over-Kelly preset. Same coin, same edge. The only difference is bet size. Look at the bankruptcy rate.</p>

        <p>Most professional gamblers bet half Kelly, not full. The next section explains why.</p>

        <div class="text-center mt-6">
          <a href="#kelly" class="text-sm text-gold" style="text-decoration: none;" id="scroll-to-s4">scroll to see why ↓</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* ─── Section 4: Full Kelly vs Half Kelly ─── */}
    <section id="kelly" class="max-w-prose mx-auto py-20 border-t border-ink/10">
      <div class="flex items-start gap-4 mb-8">
        <img src="/chip-4.png" alt="" width="48" height="48" loading="lazy" class="section-chip-img hidden sm:block" />
        <h2 class="mt-0" style="margin-top: 0;">
          <img src="/chip-4.png" alt="" width="32" height="32" loading="lazy" class="section-chip-img inline sm:hidden mr-2 align-middle" />
          Full Kelly vs Half Kelly
        </h2>
      </div>

      {/* Part 1: Opening prose */}
      <p>Every Kelly calculation depends on two numbers: the probability you win, and how much you win if you do. The simulator takes these as given. Real life doesn't.</p>

      <p>In practice, your edge is an estimate. A card counter thinks the count is favourable, but how favourable exactly? A pre-seed VC thinks 10% of investments will return 20×, but maybe it's 8%, or 13%. A sharp sports gambler thinks they're hitting 54%, but the true rate won't be revealed for thousands of bets. Every real-world Kelly calculation rests on numbers that are slightly off.</p>

      <p>This wouldn't matter if Kelly were symmetric around its peak. It isn't. Betting 20% less than optimal barely dents your long-run growth rate. Betting 20% more can push you into negative territory, where every additional round erodes your bankroll. The punishment for overshooting is much worse than the reward for hitting the mark.</p>

      <p>The chart below shows what happens to your growth rate if your edge estimate is wrong. Move the slider to vary how far off your estimate is, and watch where full Kelly lands compared to half Kelly.</p>

      {/* Part 2: Chart + Slider + Readouts */}
      <div class="mt-10">
        <div class="sim-control-group mb-6">
