      {/* Part 3: Closing prose */}
      <div class="mt-12">
        <p>Notice the asymmetry. When your edge estimate is spot on, full Kelly beats half Kelly by roughly 25%. When you're 20% over-confident - a realistic amount - full Kelly gives back almost all of that advantage, and it keeps falling from there. Half Kelly's curve is much flatter: it rewards you when you're right, and it barely punishes you when you're wrong.</p>

        <p>This is the case for half Kelly. You sacrifice a quarter of your theoretical growth rate in exchange for a simulation that doesn't explode when your inputs are slightly off. Given that your inputs are always slightly off, this is a trade professionals make without thinking.</p>

        <p>Everything so far has assumed you had an edge in the first place. The next section is about what happens when you don't.</p>
